05405nam a22007335i 9780226609607DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018029190  a97802266096077 a10.7208/97802266096072doi  a(DE-B1597)525812  a(OCoLC)1085349321  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJK1976b.H355 2019 4aJK1976b.H355 2019 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a324.9732231 aHall, Andrew B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWho Wants to Run? :bHow the Devaluing of Political Office Drives Polarization /cAndrew B. Hall. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (176 p.) :b29 line drawings, 16 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in American Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Those Fittest for the Trust -- tChapter 1. Who Wants to Run? -- tChapter 2. A Framework for Studying Elections and Ideology -- tChapter 3. The Electoral Preference for Moderates -- tChapter 4. Polarization and the Devaluing of Office -- tChapter 5. Depolarization and the Benefits of Office -- tChapter 6. Polarization and the Costs of Running -- tConclusion: Who Wants to Run? in Broader Context -- tAppendix 1: Additional Results on Polarization and Who Runs -- tAppendix 2: Estimating the Advantage of Moderates -- tAppendix 3: Effects of Office Benefits on Polarization -- tAppendix 4: State Legislators Running for the U.S. House -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe growing ideological gulf between Democrats and Republicans is one of the biggest issues in American politics today. Our legislatures, composed of members from two sharply disagreeing parties, are struggling to function as the founders intended them to. If we want to reduce the ideological gulf in our legislatures, we must first understand what has caused it to widen so much over the past forty years. Andrew B. Hall argues that we have missed one of the most important reasons for this ideological gulf: the increasing reluctance of moderate citizens to run for office. While political scientists, journalists, and pundits have largely focused on voters, worried that they may be too partisan, too uninformed to vote for moderate candidates, or simply too extreme in their own political views, Hall argues that our political system discourages moderate candidates from seeking office in the first place. Running for office has rarely been harder than it is in America today, and the costs dissuade moderates more than extremists. Candidates have to wage ceaseless campaigns, dialing for dollars for most of their waking hours while enduring relentless news and social media coverage. When moderate candidates are unwilling to run, voters do not even have the opportunity to send them to office. To understand what is wrong with our legislatures, then, we need to ask ourselves the question: who wants to run? If we want more moderate legislators, we need to make them a better job offer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aElectionszUnited States. 0aPolarization (Social sciences) 0aPolarization (Social sciences). 0aPolitical candidateszUnited States. 0aRight and left (Political science)zUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aUS House.  acampaign finance.  acongress.  aelections.  alegislatures.  apolarization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law